{"atom_id":"md_dmSE_ex_a045","file":"knowledge_base/domains/SE/examples.md","line_start":73,"line_end":73,"parent_section":"§SE.2 [Example 2]","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"**Row 1:** Shows the record for a subject who was randomized to blinded treatment A, but withdrew from the trial before the open treatment epoch and did not have a second treatment assignment. They were thus incompletely assigned to an arm. The code used to represent this incomplete assignment, \"A\", is not in the TA table for this trial design, but is the first part of the codes for the 2 arms to which subject 123 could have been assigned (\"AR\" or \"AO\").","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt_version":"P0_writer_md_v1.9.2","ts":"2026-05-07T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id":"md_dmSE_ex_a046","file":"knowledge_base/domains/SE/examples.md","line_start":75,"line_end":75,"parent_section":"§SE.2 [Example 2]","atom_type":"SENTENCE","verbatim":"**Row 2:** Shows the record for a subject who was randomized to blinded treatment A, but was erroneously treated with drug B for part of the blinded treatment epoch. ARM and ARMCD for this subject reflect the planned treatment and are not affected by the fact that treatment deviated from plan. The sponsor decided that the subject's treatment, which consisted partly of drug A and partly of drug B, did not match any planned arm, so ACTARMCD and ACTARM were left null. ARMNRS was populated with \"UNPLANNED TREATMENT\" and the way in which this treatment was unplanned was described in ACTARMUD.","heading_level":null,"sibling_index":null,"figure_ref":null,"cross_refs":[],"extracted_by":{"subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt_version":"P0_writer_md_v1.9.2","ts":"2026-05-07T00:00:00Z"}}
